Introduction
============

Memories are believed to be stored in synapses, encoded as changes in
synaptic strength
[@hebb_organization_2005; @takeuchi_synaptic_2014; @choi_interregional_2018].
[ltp]{acronym-label="ltp" acronym-form="singular+short"}, an activity
dependent change in synaptic strength, is considered to be the primary
post-synaptic memory mechanism
[@bliss_expression_2013; @mayford_synapses_2012]. Various behavioural
experiments strongly suggest a critical role for
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} in
induction of [ltp]{acronym-label="ltp" acronym-form="singular+short"}
[@lucchesi_novel_2011; @giese_autophosphorylation_1998]. In the CA1
region of Hippocampus, blocking [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activity blocks the induction of
[ltp]{acronym-label="ltp" acronym-form="singular+short"}
[@chang_camkii_2017]. After LTP induction, several other pathways
including protein synthesis [@aslam_translational_2009], clustering of
receptors [@shouval_clusters_2005], receptor translocation
[@hayer_molecular_2005] and PKM-$\zeta$ activation
[@sacktor_memory_2012], have been suggested as mechanisms for long-term
maintenance of synaptic state. Recent evidence from behavioural assays
suggests that [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} may also be involved in long-term
maintenance of memory [@rossetti_memory_2017] (but see
[@chang_camkii_2017]).

Any putative molecular mechanism involved in long-term maintenance of
memory must be able to maintain its state despite the potent resetting
mechanisms of chemical noise and protein turnover. In the small volume
of the synapse ($\sim$ 0.02 [@bartol_nanoconnectomic_2015]), the number
of molecules involved in biochemical processes range from single digits
to a few hundred, thereby increasing the effect of chemical noise. John
Lisman proposed that a kinase and its phosphatase could form a bistable
molecular switch able to maintain its state for a very long time despite
turnover [@lisman_mechanism_1985]. It has been shown by various
mathematical models that [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} and its phosphatase
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} may form a
bistable switch [@zhabotinsky_bistability_2000] which can retain its
state for years despite stochastic chemical noise and protein turnover
[@miller_stability_2005]. Although there is experimental evidence that
CaMKII/PP1 is bistable in *in vitro* settings
[@bradshaw_ultrasensitive_2003; @urakubo_vitro_2014], experimental
evidence for *in vivo* bistability is lacking. In spine cytosol,
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} has been
shown not to act like a bistable switch but rather a leaky integrator of
calcium activity [@chang_camkii_2017]. However,
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} may be
bistable in special micro-environments such as the "core"
[psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"} where it
attaches to NMDA receptor
[@dosemeci_postsynaptic_2016; @petersen_distribution_2003].

From a computational perspective, the CaMKII/PP1 bistable system is an
attractive candidate for memory storage [@koch_biophysics_2004].
Bistability provides a plausible solution to the problem of state
maintenance. Previous modeling work has shown that the CaMKII/PP1 system
may form a very stable switch despite protein turnover and stochastic
noise in the small volume of the synapse. The stability increases
exponentially with the number of holoenzymes [@miller_stability_2005].
It is important to note that this model exhibits bistable behaviour only
in a narrow range of [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} concentrations in the
[psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"}. This strict
restriction may be met because phosphorylated
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} is
protected from phosphatases in [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} except [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} [@strack_differential_1997] which is
tightly regulated in the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} [@bollen_extended_2010].

[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} has
another remarkable property which was hypothesized by Lisman
[@lisman_cam_1994] but discovered only recently, namely, subunit
exchange. In this process, two [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} holoenzymes can exchange active subunits
leading to spread of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activation
[@stratton_activation-triggered_2014].

In this paper, we adapt the [mz]{acronym-label="mz"
acronym-form="singular+short"} [@miller_stability_2005] to include
subunit exchange and diffusion, and quantify the effects of subunit
exchange on the properties of the [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"}-[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} PP1 system in two adjacent neuronal
micro-environments: [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} and spine cytosol.

In the [psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"},
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} is tightly
regulated and [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} is protected from other phosphatases. But
in the spine cytosol, [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} is accessible to other phosphatases along
with [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}. We
examined how state switching lifetimes in the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} are affected by subunit exchange in
different contexts of [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} levels, turnover, and clustering of
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}. In the
spine cytosol we show how the integration of calcium stimuli generates
two time-courses of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activity as a result of subunit exchange
[@chang_camkii_2017].

Results {#sec:results}
=======

Model validation {#subsec:model-validation}
----------------

The basic computational units in our model are individual
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} subunits,
and [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} ring
consisting of 6 or 7 [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} subunits. We treat the
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} ring as a
proxy for the [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} holoenzyme, which consists of two such
rings stacked over each other
[@woodgett_calmodulin-dependent; @hoelz_crystal_2003; @chao_mechanism_2011].
In our model, [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} exists in 15 possible states compared to
2 in the [mz]{acronym-label="mz" acronym-form="singular+short"} model
(see ). This leads to many more reactions than the
[mz]{acronym-label="mz" acronym-form="singular+short"} model. We also
replaced Michaelis-Menten approximation in the [mz]{acronym-label="mz"
acronym-form="singular+short"} model by equivalent mass-action kinetics
(e.g., ). Since analytical comparison of the two models was not
possible, we first compared numerical results from our model without
diffusion and without subunit exchange with the [mz]{acronym-label="mz"
acronym-form="singular+short"} model ().

Our model exhibited all the key properties of the
[mz]{acronym-label="mz" acronym-form="singular+short"} model: 1. In
[psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"}, under basal
[ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} stimulus
conditions, CaMKII/PP1 formed a bistable switch (C, D), 2. The stability
of the switch increased exponentially with system size (E), 3. Increased
number of [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}
molecules (N~PP1~) shut off the switch (), and, 4. Bistability was
robust to slow turnover of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} ().

Thus, our baseline model exhibited all the key properties that had
previously been predicted for the bistable
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} switch.
However, subunit exchange and diffusion introduced several interesting
additional properties, which we examine below.

