](PaperFigures/elifeFigure2/figure_effect_of_tolerace_140mm.pdf){width="140mm"}

[\[fig:tolerance\_pp1\]]{#fig:tolerance_pp1 label="fig:tolerance_pp1"}

We first analyzed switch sensitivity to [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"}. In our model as well in the
[mz]{acronym-label="mz" acronym-form="singular+short"} model, the number
of PP1 molecules (N~PP1~) has an upper limit for the switch to exhibit
bistability. This constraint arises because [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} must saturate in the `ON` state of the
switch, i.e., the maximal enzymatic turnover of
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} must be smaller
than the rate of activation of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} subunits. However, unlike the
[mz]{acronym-label="mz" acronym-form="singular+short"} model where the
addition of one extra [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} molecule changed the residence time of
the `ON` state by roughly 90% (Figure 2C in [@miller_stability_2005]),
we did not find the residence time of the `ON` state to be this
sensitive to [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}.
In our model, on average it required 0.5$\times$N~CaMKII~ extra
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} molecules to
cause a similar 90% change in the residence time of the `ON` state. This
number is roughly equal to the maximum number of
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} subunits
(released from [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} holoenzymes during subunit exchange )
that can exist at any given time in our model. We conjecture that this
reduced sensitivity to [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} is due to the fact that
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} participates in
many more reactions in our model.

We found that a system consisting of N~CaMKII~ holoenzymes remained
bistable for N~PP1~=8$\times$ to 15$\times$N~CaMKII~ without subunit
exchange, and for N~PP1~=12$\times$ to 21$\times$N~CaMKII~ with subunit
exchange. Thus, subunit exchange shifted the bistable range to higher
values of [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}.
Nevertheless, the gap between the upper and lower limit remained the
same in both cases (blue and red sigmoidal fit in B).

In the presence of subunit exchange, the `ON` state of switch has
tighter distribution (blue v/s red histogram, A) i.e., there are fewer
holoenzymes being completely de-phosphorylated by
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}. Any subunit in
a holoenzyme de-phosphorylated by the [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} is more likely to be phosphorylated back
in the presence of subunit exchange. Because when the switch is in `ON`
state, most subunits floating around in the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} are in the phosphorylated state and
hence, in addition to auto-phosphorylation, the exchange reactions ()
turn unphosphorylated holoenzymes to phosphorylated holoenzymes with a
significant rate (data not shown). Taken together, subunit exchange acts
as a compensatory mechanism for dephosphorylation by
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} in the `ON`
state of the switch.

Subunit exchange also had a strong effect on time spent by the switch in
transition from one stable state to another (relaxation time). When
subunit exchange was enabled, the relaxation time was reduced (red v/s
blue dotted line in B) and also became independent of N~PP1~. As
mentioned previously, due to subunit exchange, the `ON` state has
tighter distribution (blue v/s red histogram in A) which means that
there were fewer number of ineffective transition from `ON` to `OFF`
state. Expectedly the standard deviation of the relaxation time was also
greatly reduced in the presence of subunit exchange (red and blue curve,
C). Thus subunit exchange makes the switch's `ON` state less noisy or
more robust to dephosphorylation by [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"}.

Parallel results were obtained for the effect of subunit exchange on
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} switch
robustness in the context of protein turnover. Turnover replaces any
active [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
holoenzyme by an inactive holoenzyme with a constant rate (), thus
decreasing the stability of the `ON` state. Without subunit exchange,
switch stability as measured by residence time of the `ON` state
decreased exponentially with increasing turnover rate. With subunit
exchange, however, residence time of the `ON` state remained roughly
constant upto a $\sim$10 fold increase in turnover (B), after which
subunit exchange could not phosphorylate all inactive holoenzymes
produced by turnover, and the switch started to show similar exponential
decay of stability as before. As expected, turnover increased the number
of switching events in the regime of bistability in both cases.

