Thus, subunit exchange increases the range of N~PP1~ and turnover rate
over which the switch remains bistable. It also reduces fluctuations in
the switch's `ON` state.

Subunit exchange facilitates the spread of CaMKII activity {#res:spread_activity}
----------------------------------------------------------

As suggested in [@stratton_activation-triggered_2014], we found that
subunit exchange facilitated spread of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activation (). When subunits were allowed
to diffuse, an active subunit could be picked by a neighbouring inactive
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
holoenzymes making it partially phosphorylated. This can effectively
overcome the first slow step of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} phosphorylation () when many
phosphorylated subunits are available, thereby facilitating the spread
of activation.

We simulated N~CaMKII~=18 inactive holoenzymes in a cylinderical arena
with a volume of 0.0275 and a length of 540 nm representing the
[psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"}. The cylinder
was divided into 18 voxels (1 holoenzyme in each voxel). Each voxel was
separated by 30 nm, which is the average nearest-neighbour distance for
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
holoenzymes [@feng_quantitative_2011]. Each voxel was considered to be a
*well-mixed* environment i.e., diffusion was instantaneous within the
voxel. Between voxels, diffusion was implemented as cross-voxel "jump"
reactions (See ). We did not try 2D/3D diffusion because of its
simulation complexity and because it would be expected to be
qualitatively similar [@fange_stochastic_2010].

We fixed the diffusion coefficient of [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} (D~PP1~) to quantify the effect of
varying the diffusion coefficient of subunits (D~sub~) and basal calcium
levels. We used D~PP1~=0.5 which is the observed value of the diffusion
coefficient of Ras, a similar sized protein [@harvey_spread_2008]. We
ran simulations for 4 hours at basal calcium concentration
\[[ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"}\]=80 M+$\epsilon$ and without subunit
exchange (i.e., D~sub~=0). We set N~PP1~=15$\times$N~CaMKII~ to make
sure the system showed no significant [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activity (A, red curve). This served as
the baseline to quantify the effect of subunit exchange. When we enabled
subunit exchange by setting D~sub~=0.1, [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activity rose to maximum within 4 h for
even low value of D~sub~=0.001 (C, black and brown curves).

Expectedly, at higher basal [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"} level (120 M), system showed higher
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} activity
for all values of D~sub~ (D). Increasing D~sub~ increased the effect of
subunit exchange (decreased rise time of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activity from 10% to 90%, D). However the
time of onset of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activation as measured by rise time from
0% to 10% was only dependant only on basal [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"} levels but not on D~sub~ (E).

Thus, subunit exchange facilitates the spread of kinase activity post
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
activation but does not affect the onset of
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
activation.

