Next we probed the effect of subunit exchange between spatially
separated [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
clusters. We considered N~CaMKII~ holoenzymes organized into three
clusters of size N~CaMKII~/3, each separated by a distance $d$. This
configuration corresponds to cases where receptors and
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
holoenzymes are clustered at the synapse.

When there is no subunit exchange across voxels (D~sub~=0), these
switches are expected to switch independently like multiple coins
flipped together, resulting in a binomial distribution of activity. The
clustered system had 3 relatively stable bistable systems (long
residence time, E). As expected, without subunit exchange, activity in
this system had a binomial distribution (B, red plot).

Then we allowed [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}
and [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
subunits to undergo linear diffusion. We set D~PP1~=0.5 as before and
varied D~sub~ to quantify effect of subunit exchange. Subunit exchange
led to synchronization of switching activity. The population of
clustered [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
acted as a single bistable switch (B, blue plot). This effect was strong
and robust to variation in D~sub~. Even for a very small value of
D~sub~=0.01, we observed strong synchronization (D). The synchronization
disappeared completely for D~sub~ less than e-4, and for $d$ greater
than 100 nm (D).

Thus, for most physiologically plausible values of diffusion coefficient
D~sub~, subunit exchange causes synchronization of switching activity of
clustered [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"}.

Subunit exchange may account for the observed dual decay rate of CaMKII phosphorylation {#subsec:camkii_decay_two_time_course}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Finally, we asked if subunit exchange might account for the complex
time-course of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} dynamics in spine as observed in recent
experiments [@chang_camkii_2017]. We designed a simulation to replicate
an experiment where [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} was inhibited by a genetically encoded
photoactivable inhibitory peptide after activating
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} by
glutamate uncaging [@murakoshi_kinetics_2017]. In the spine,
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} is more
accessible to phosphatases than in the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"}, where our previous calculations had been
located. To model the increased availability of phosphatases, we
increased the concentration of [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
