We expected subunit exchange to have a strong effect on the decay
activity of clustered [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} in spine cytosol (e.g.,
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} bound to
actin) because of the proximity of holoenzymes, leading to rapid
exchange. Thus, if there are populations of clustered as well as
non-clustered [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} in the spine, we expected that they would
exhibit long and short time-courses of activity decay, respectively.
Therefore a mixed population of clustered and non-clustered
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} should
decay with two time-constants. Our simulations supported this
prediction.

In [@chang_camkii_2017], the decay kinetics of
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} were
obtained by curve fitting of experimental data. It is given by a
double-exponential function:
$F(t)=P_{fast}e^{-t/\tau_{fast}}+P_{slow}e^{-t/\tau_{slow}}$ where
$P_{fast}=0.74, P_{slow}=0.26, \tau_{fast}= 6.4\pm0.7 \si{\second},
\tau_{slow}=92.6 \pm 50.7\si{\second}$ (C, magenta). We used their
estimate of $P_{fast}$ and $P_{slow}$ to construct a mixed population of
slow and fast decaying [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} (A, black) and estimated a
double-exponential function which fits it (C, dashed red). The
time-constants obtained (8.4 s, 86.2 s) matched well with experimentally
estimated time-constants of (6.4 s$\pm$0.7, 92.6 s$\pm$50.7).

Thus, we suggest that subunit exchange may be a mechanism that leads to
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}$\alpha$
activity decaying with two time-courses in spine cytosol.

Discussion
==========

Here we have shown that subunit exchange strongly affects the properties
of the CaMKII/PP1 pathway, both in its role as a bistable switch in the
PSD and as a leaky integrator of [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activity in spine cytosol. In the PSD,
where the model was tuned to elicit bistable dynamics from clustered
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}, subunit
exchange improved the stability of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"}/[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} switch by synchronizing the kinase
activity across the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} (). It also improved active
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} tolerance
of PP1 and turnover rate ( and ). In the case where
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} was
uniformly distributed in [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"}, subunit exchange facilitated more rapid
activation of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} (B-D)
[@stratton_activation-triggered_2014]. These simulation results predict
that a [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
mutant lacking subunit exchange would be deficient in switch stability
and slower to be activated by [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"} thereby resulting in degraded memory
retention and deficient learning in memory related behavioural
experiments, respectively.

In the spine head, subunit exchange facilitated integration by
prolonging the decay time-course of kinase activity (). The fact that
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} dynamics
changed from an integrator to bistable switch as we moved from spine
cytosol (a phosphatase rich environment) to the
[psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"} (where PP1 is
tightly controlled) suggests an interesting sub-compartmentalization of
functions in these microdomains. Furthermore, we observed that the
clustering of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} had important implications for its
sustained activity.

Subunit exchange is unlikely to have any impact on neighbouring spines.
The mean escape time of a single [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} subunit from a typical spine is between
8 s to 33 s [@holcman_diffusion_2011]. In a real synapse, this time
would be even larger given that [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} interacts with many other molecules. Any
phosphorylated subunit is almost certain to be de-phosphorylated by
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} during this
time. We therefore predict that the effects of synchronization are local
to each [psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"}, where
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} is known to be
tightly controlled. Subunit exchange loses its potency in the
phosphatase rich region of the bulk spine head or dendrite. We therefore
consider it unlikely that [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} subunit exchange plays any role in
intra-spine information exchange such as synaptic tagging.

[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} is non
uniformly distributed in the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} where it is mostly concentrated in a
small region of 16 nm to 36 nm below synaptic cleft
[@petersen_distribution_2003]. In the [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"}, [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} may exist in large clusters given that
the [psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"} is rich in
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} binding
partners. Our study predicts that subunit exchange may lead to
synchronization when [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} is clustered, or more rapid activation by
[ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} when it is
uniformly distributed. Given that [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} can form clusters with
[nmda]{acronym-label="nmda" acronym-form="singular+short"} receptors, it
would be interesting to study the mixed case where some
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} is
clustered and the rest is uniformly distributed. This would require a
detailed 3D simulation and is beyond the scope of this study.

Finally, we suggest that the existence of diverse multiple time-scales
of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
activity -- bistable and highly stable synchronized bistable in PSD,
slow and fast decaying leaky integrator in spine head -- has important
theoretical implications. A very plastic synapse is good at registering
activity dependent changes (learning) but poor at retaining old
memories. On the other hand, a rigid synapse is good at retaining old
memories but is not efficient at learning. A theoretical meta-model
which sought to strike a balance between these two competing demands
requires that a diversity of timescales must exist at the synapse
[@benna_computational_2016] for optimum performance. In this model,
complex synapses with state variables with diverse time-scales are shown
to form a memory network in which storage capacity scales linearly with
the number of synapses, and memory decay follows $1/\sqrt{t}$ --- a
power-law supported by psychological studies [@wixted_form_1991]. This
model requires the memory trace to be first stored in a fast variable
and then progressively and efficiently transferred to slower variables.
Our study suggests a concrete mechanism for such a process. Here, the
[ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} concentration in
the PSD can be mapped to the fastest variable. The
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
integrator in the cytosol could represent the second slower variable to
which the trace is transferred from [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"}. Further, the state information is
transferred to the third slower [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} bistable switch. The dynamics of
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} in the
PSD forms an even slower bistable variable for longer retention of the
memory trace. It is possible that memory is transferred from here to
even slower variables, such as sustained receptor insertion
[@hayer_molecular_2005], PKM-$\zeta$ activation [@sacktor_memory_2012],
or local protein synthesis [@aslam_translational_2009].

Methods and Materials
=====================

[\[sec:materials\_and\_methods\]]{#sec:materials_and_methods
label="sec:materials_and_methods"}

We extended Miller and Zhabotinksy (MZ model) [@miller_stability_2005]
to incorporate *subunit exchange* and diffusion. We assume that vertical
dimers are inserted and released together
[@bhattacharyya_molecular_2016]. We also assume that both subunits of a
vertical dimer phosphorylate and de-phosphorylate together. Under this
assumption, we can treat the [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} ring as the proxy for the
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
holoenzyme and the subunit as the proxy for the
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} dimer.
Without this assumption, the simulation cost of the increased complexity
would be very significant. The qualitative aspect of model behaviour
will be the same with or without this assumption.

In our model, a [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} ring with $n$ subunits ($n$=6 or 7) can
exist in 15 different states enumerated as $x_{a}y_{n-a}$ for
$0 \le a \le n$ where $x$ and $y$ represents un-phosphorylated and
phosphorylated subunits respectively. We ignore all rotational
permutations and kinetically unlikely cases where there are
discontiguous phosphorylated subunits in the ring. We assumed that the
phosphorylation of neighbouring subunit proceeds clockwise.

Ca^2+^ background activity ($\epsilon$) {#subsec:calcium_background}
---------------------------------------

We assumed the resting [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"} level in spine to be 80 M
[@berridge_neuronal_1998]. In [mz]{acronym-label="mz"
acronym-form="singular+short"} model, Miller *et al.* assumed that
[ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} entry through
[nmda]{acronym-label="nmda" acronym-form="singular+short"} receptors can
be approximated by a Poisson train with an average rate of 0.5 Hz.
Since, on average, $\sim$0.5 [nmda]{acronym-label="nmda"
acronym-form="singular+short"} receptor opens [@nimchinsky_number_2004]
upon pre-synaptic stimulation, we reduced the frequency of NMDA opening
events to 0.25 Hz. We used a periodic pulse with time-period of 4 s and
duty cycle of 50%. To model NMDA activity in 2 s long `ON` period of our
4 s long periodic pulse, we sampled from a uniform distribution with
median of 120 M (50% change, on average) and range of 40 M (C). This
distribution is informed by figure 2B,C from [@nimchinsky_number_2004].

We did not consider decay dynamics of [ca]{acronym-label="ca"
acronym-form="singular+short"} influx through
[nmda]{acronym-label="nmda" acronym-form="singular+short"} channel since
including the timescale of decay (roughly 100 ms) would have made
simulation very slow. The effect of ignoring decay dynamics are expected
to be negligible given the time-scale of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} activation is much larger than the time
course of [ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} decay
dynamics. Furthermore, we did not consider contributions to background
[ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} fluctuations by
other channels. This background activity is represented by $\epsilon$ in
other figures.

Phosphorylation and dephosphorylation of CaMKII ring {#phosphorylation-and-dephosphorylation-of-ring}
----------------------------------------------------

The activation of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} follows the same dynamics as in
[mz]{acronym-label="mz" acronym-form="singular+short"} model (). In this
paper, by phosphorylation/activation of a
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"} subunit
or a holoenzyme, we mean phosphorylation at Thr^286^. The first step in
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
activation requires simultaneous binding of two
[cacam]{acronym-label="cacam" acronym-form="singular+short"} to the two
adjacent subunits of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"}. Once a subunit is phosphorylated
(Thr^286^), it catalyzes phosphorylation of it's neighbour
(*auto-phosphorylation*) which requires binding of only one
[cacam]{acronym-label="cacam" acronym-form="singular+short"}. Therefore,
further phosphorylation proceeds at much faster rate. The
phosphorylation of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} (Thr^286^) is given by
[@bradshaw_ultrasensitive_2003; @miller_stability_2005].

$$\label{eq:phospho}
    \newcommand\CaHILL{\ensuremath{\frac{Ca^{2+}}{K_{H1}}}}
    \newcommand\VONE{k_1 \left[\frac{H^3}{1+H^3}\right]^2}
    \newcommand\VTWO{k_1\frac{H^3}{1+H ^3}}
\begin{gathered}
    x_ay_{n-a} \xrightarrow{v_1} x_{a-1}y_{n-a+1} \xrightarrow{v_2} x_{a-2}y_{n-a+2} \\
    v_1 = \VONE,\, v_2 =\VTWO,\,\text{where}\; H=\CaHILL
\end{gathered}$$ where $n=6\;\text{or}\;7$ for $1\le a \le n$;
$k_1=\SI{1.5}{\per\second}$ [@hanson_dual_1994], and
$k_{H1}=\SI{0.7}{\micro M}$
[@koninck_sensitivity_1998; @miller_stability_2005]. At resting
[ca]{acronym-label="ca" acronym-form="singular+short"} concentration of
100 M, $v_1=\SI{1.27e-5}{\per\second}$ and
$v_2=\SI{4.36e-3}{\per\second}$ (i.e., ${v_2}/{v_1}\approx 343$).

Once fully phosphorylated, [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} moves to [psd]{acronym-label="psd"
acronym-form="singular+short"} where it binds to
[nmda]{acronym-label="nmda" acronym-form="singular+short"} receptor.
Upon binding, it is no longer accessible other phosphatases save
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}.

The dephosphorylation of the [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} ring, and the subunit is given by .

$$\label{eq:dephosphorylation} 
    \begin{gathered} 
        PP1 + x_ay_{n-a} \xrightleftharpoons[k^-]{k^+} PP1.x_ay_{n-a} 
            \xrightarrow{k_2} PP1 + x_{a+1}y_{n-a-1} \\ 
        PP1 + x \xrightleftharpoons[k^-]{k^+} PP1.x \xrightarrow{k_2} PP1 + y 
    \end{gathered}$$

where $n=6\;\text{or}\;7$, and $1\le a \le n$. Following
[@miller_stability_2005], we also assumed $k^-=0$. This gave us
$k^+=\frac{k_2}{k_M}=\SI{1}{\per\micro M\per\second}$. We could not find
any experimental estimate of $k_M$ in recent literature, therefore we
used the same value of $k_M$ used in the [mz]{acronym-label="mz"
acronym-form="singular+short"} model [@miller_stability_2005].

Subunit exchange {#subunit exchange}
----------------

Since [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
ring consists of either 6 or 7 subunits exists in our model, any ring
with 6 subunits cannot lose a subunit, and a ring with 7 subunits cannot
gain a subunit. The reactions which result in either gain or lose of a
subunit are given by where $0\le a \le 6\text{ or }7$.

$$\label{eq:losegainx}
    \begin{gathered}
    x_ay_{7-a} + x \xrightleftharpoons[k^-_x]{k^+_x} x_{a+1}y_{6-a} \\
    x_ay_{6-a} + y \xrightleftharpoons[k^-_y]{k^+_y} x_{a}y_{7-a}
    \end{gathered}$$

The values of $k_x^+$, $k_x^-$, $k_y^+$, and $k_y^-$ are not available
in the literature that we are aware of. We used the data in
[@stratton_activation-triggered_2014] to estimate the possible timescale
of subunit exchange rate. [@bhattacharyya_molecular_2016] speculate that
upon activation, the hub of holoenzyme becomes less stable and more
likely to open up and lose a subunit i.e., active holoenzyme loses a
subunit faster. Therefore, we maintained the following ratio
$k_x^- \approx 10 k_x^+ N_{\text{CaMKII}}$ and
$k_y^- \approx 10 k_y^+ N_{\text{CaMKII}}$ in all simulations where
N~CaMKII~ is the number of holoenzymes in the system.

### Estimation of subunit exchange rate {#subsec:estimate_exchange_rate}

To estimate reaction rates of , we modeled the \"single molecule assay\"
used in [@stratton_activation-triggered_2014]. In this assay, two
distinct populations of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} labelled by either green or red
fluorophores were mixed together. The holoenzymes were not free to move
but release subunits could move freely. A green holoenzyme may pick up a
red subunit and vice versa thereby giving rise to a mixed colored
population. The readout from this assay is called "cololocalization"
which is the fraction of total holoenzymes containing subunits of both
colors.

In our model of this assay, a [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} holoenzyme is represented by $R_aG_{n-a}$
where $R$ and $G$ represent a red and a green subunit in the holoenzyme
respectively, and $n=6\;\text{or}\;7$. The green population consists of
holoenzymes with only green subunits (i.e., $R_0G_6$ and $R_0G_7$) and
the red population has holoenzymes with all red subunits (i.e., $R_6G_0$
or $R_7G_0$). We assume that each color population has equal number of
dodecameric (n=6) and tetradecameric (n=7) holoenzymes. Upon mixing red
and green populations, following reactions take place.

$$\label{eq:mixing_assay}
    \begin{gathered}
        R_aG_b \xrightleftharpoons[r_g]{r_l} R_{a-1}G_b + R 
        \quad \text{for all}\; a>0,b\ge 0\; \text{s.t.}\; a+b=6 \\
        R_aG_b \xrightleftharpoons[r_g]{r_l} R_{a}G_{b-1} + G 
        \quad \text{for all}\; a\ge 0,b> 0\; \text{s.t.}\; a+b=7
    \end{gathered}$$

The value of colocalization is equal to the percentage of all
holoenzymes containing at least one red and one green subunit i.e.
$\frac{\sum_{a\ge 1, b
\ge 1} [R_aG_b]}{ \sum_{a\ge0,b \ge 0}[R_aG_b]}$. We simulated the
reaction network given by for various values of $r_l$ and $r_g$ (B) and
found the values of $r_g$ and $r_l$ which described the data in
[@stratton_activation-triggered_2014] reasonably well.

First we explored the space of $r_l$ and $r_g$ for which the time
constant of colocalization dynamics matched well with the experimental
data for \[[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
