PP1 deactivation {#subsec:pp1_deactivation}
----------------

In the [psd]{acronym-label="psd" acronym-form="singular+short"},
[pp1]{acronym-label="pp1" acronym-form="singular+short"} is the primary
-- and perhaps only -- phosphatase known to dephosphorylate
[camkii]{acronym-label="camkii" acronym-form="singular+short"}
[@strack_translocation_1997]. We followed [mz]{acronym-label="mz"
acronym-form="singular+short"} model for where [i1]{acronym-label="i1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} inactivates [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"}. [i1p]{acronym-label="i1p"
acronym-form="singular+short"} renders [pp1]{acronym-label="pp1"
acronym-form="singular+short"} inactive by forming
[i1ppp1]{acronym-label="i1ppp1" acronym-form="singular+short"}.

$$\label{eq:i1pandpp1}
    \begin{gathered}
        PP1 + I1P \xrightleftharpoons[k_4]{k_3} I1P.PP1 \\
        I1P = I1 \frac{v_{PKA}}{v_{CaN}} 
            \frac{1+\left(\frac{Ca}{k_{H2}}\right)^3}{\left(\frac{Ca}{k_{H2}}\right)^3}
    \end{gathered}$$

where $k_3=\SI{100}{\per\micro M\per\second}$,
$k_4=\SI{0.1}{\per\second}$ [@endo_multiple_1996], and
$v_{PKA}/v_{CaN}=1$ [@miller_stability_2005].

Turnover
--------

The turnover of [camkii]{acronym-label="camkii"
acronym-form="singular+short"} is a continuous process given by with
rate $v_{t}=\SI{30}{\per\hour}$ [@ehlers_activity_2003].

$$\label{eq:turnover}
    \begin{gathered}
        x_ay_{6-a} \xrightarrow{v_t} x_6y_0\; \text{for}\; 6\ge a\ge 1 \\
        x_ay_{7-a} \xrightarrow{v_t} x_7y_0\; \text{for}\; 7\ge a\ge 1
    \end{gathered}$$

Diffusion and simulation method {#subsec:simulator}
-------------------------------

Diffusion is implemented as cross voxel "jump" reaction. Diffusion of a
species X with diffusion-coefficient D~X~ between voxel A and B
separated by distance $h$ is modelled by reaction
$X_A \xrightleftharpoons[k]{k} X_B$ where $k={D_X}/{h^2}$, and
$[X_A]=[X_B]=[X]/2$ [@erban_practical_2007]. Based on our own numerical
results () and other studies
[@isaacson_reaction-diffusion_2009; @erban_stochastic_2009], we are
confident that $h \ge 10h_{crit}$ where
$h_{crit}=\frac{k^+}{D_{PP1}+D_{sub}}$ is a good value. We have
$h_{crit} \le \SI{3.2}{\nano\meter}$ whenever
$D_{PP1}+D_{sub}\ge\SI{0.5}{\micro\meter\squared\per\second}$. For all
simulations presented in main text, we maintain $h\ge h_{crit}$. For a
case where $h$ is smaller than $h_{crit}$ in some trajectories see .

All simulations were performed using Stochastic solver (Gillespie
method) available in MOOSE simulator (<https://moose.ncbs.res.in>,
version 3.1.4) [@ray_pymoose:_2008]. This model is available at
<https://github.com/dilawar/SinghAndBhalla_CaMKII_SubunitExchange_2018>.
Table of parameters can be found in SI ().

